        ", the de facto head of the Soviet film industry, finally called a halt to the filming and cancelled further production. What appeared to save Eisensteins career at this point was that Stalin ended up taking the position that the Bezhin Meadow catastrophe, along with several other problems facing the industry at that point, had less to do with Eisensteins approach to filmmaking as with the executives who were supposed to have been supervising him. Ultimately this came down on the shoulders of Shumyatsky,  who in early 1938 was denounced, arrested, tried and convicted as a traitor, and shot.       Eisenstein was thence able to ingratiate himself with Stalin for one more chance, and he chose, from two offerings, the assignment of a biopic of  Alexander Nevsky , with music composed by ": null
    },
